Analysis

We began by looking at a few of the basic graphs for our data to get a better sense of our dependent variable Popularity since its is a very subjective term. We look at the most popular and least popular songs from out dataset.

Most Popular Songs

spotify.df.filtered.popularity = spotify.df %>% filter(popularity <= 100) %>% 
    filter(track_name != "In My Feelings")
top_n(spotify.df.filtered.popularity, n = 10, spotify.df.filtered.popularity$popularity) %>% 
    ggplot(., aes(x = track_name, y = popularity)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", 
    fill = "blue") + coord_flip() + labs(x = "Track Name", y = "Popularity", 
    title = "Most popular songs")

Least Popular Songs

top_n(spotify.df.filtered.popularity, n = -10, spotify.df.filtered.popularity$popularity) %>% 
    ggplot(., aes(x = track_name, y = popularity)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", 
    fill = "red") + coord_flip() + labs(x = "Track Name", y = "Popularity", 
    title = "Least popular songs")

a = ggplot(spotify.df, aes(x = popularity, color = genre))

a + geom_density(size = 1) + labs(x = "Popularity", y = "Density", title = "Density of Popularity for different Genres") +

spotify.model.df = spotify.df %>% dplyr::select(-duration_ms, -loudness, -speechiness, 
    -liveness, -tempo, -track_name)

Popularity by Valence for different Genres

Linear model

\(Prediction = lm(duration*(loudness + liveness + Tempo + Dancibility) + Valence + Genre + Acousticness + Dancibilty + mode + speechiness)\)

spotify.lm = lm(popularity ~ duration_s * (loudness.level + liveness.level + 
    tempo.level + danceability) + valence + genre + acousticness + danceability + 
    mode + speechiness.level, data = spotify.model.df)
summary(spotify.lm)

### Predicted values
spotify.model.df$predictions = predict(spotify.lm, spotify.model.df[, -spotify.model.df$popularity])

spotify.lm.df = augment(spotify.lm)

ggplot(spotify.lm.df, aes(x = duration_s, y = .resid)) + geom_point(size = 0.1) + 
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) + labs(x = "Duration (in secs)", 
    y = "Residual", title = "Residual of linear model")

# residual is evenly distributed indicating linear model is a good fit for
# this data
ggplot(data = spotify.model.df, aes(x = duration_s, y = popularity)) + geom_point(size = 0.1) + 
    geom_point(size = 0.1) + geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "green") + facet_wrap(~genre, 
    nrow = 1) + labs(x = "Duration (in secs)", y = "Actual Popularity", title = "Actual Popularity by Duration for different Genres") + 
    ylim(0, 100)

# print(p)
ggplot(data = spotify.model.df, aes(x = duration_s, y = predictions)) + geom_point(size = 0.1) + 
    geom_point(size = 0.1) + geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "red") + facet_wrap(~genre, 
    nrow = 1) + labs(x = "Duration (in secs)", y = "Predicted Popularity", title = "Predicted Popularity by Duration for different Genres") + 
    ylim(0, 100)

ggplot(spotify.model.df, aes(tempo.level, genre, legend = "Popularity")) + geom_tile(aes(fill = popularity)) + 
    labs(x = "Tempo", y = "Genre", title = "Actual Popularity for different combination of Tempo and Genre", 
        fill = "Actual Popularity")

ggplot(spotify.model.df, aes(tempo.level, genre)) + geom_tile(aes(fill = predictions)) + 
    labs(x = "Tempo", y = "Genre", title = "Predicted Popularity for different combination of Tempo and Genre", 
        fill = "Predicted Popularity")

ggplot(spotify.model.df, aes(speechiness.level, loudness.level)) + geom_tile(aes(fill = popularity))

Making predictions for songs

spotify.df.prediction = spotify.model.df[, !colnames(spotify.model.df) %in% 
    c("predictions")]
spotify.df.prediction = spotify.df %>% dplyr::select(c(colnames(spotify.df.prediction), 
    "track_name"))
# spotify.df.prediction =
# spotify.df.prediction[,-spotify.df.prediction$popularity]
spotify.df.prediction$predictions = predict(spotify.lm, newdata = spotify.df.prediction[, 
    !colnames(spotify.df.prediction) %in% c("predictions", "track_name")])

# Creating songs popularity and predictions dataframe
song.df = spotify.df.prediction[, c("track_name", "popularity", "predictions")]

write.csv(song.df, "song.predictions.data.csv")
